content_s: That this House appreciates the regular interventions of Mr Speaker to encourage honourable Members
content_t: That this House appreciates the regular interventions of Mr Speaker to encourage honourable Members to ask succinct questions and for Ministers to respond in similar ways, thus enabling more honourable Members to be called during question times and in response to Ministerial statements; accepts the wise words of Plato (Protagoras 3429 - 3436) 'that the art of framing brief, taut and telling phrases is a mark of the highest culture'; and affirms its intention to now pursue the precept of Plato for 'laconic brevity'.

content_s: That this House believes that Planning Use Class A3, under the Town and Country Planning (Use Classe
content_t: That this House believes that Planning Use Class A3, under the Town and Country Planning (Use Classes) Order 1987, is too wide, permitting change of use between restaurants, snack bars, hot food take away shops,  wine bars and public houses; notes that independent research carried out by the Department of the Environment found that hot food take aways had different planning implications, namely consistent late night noise and traffic parking problems; and calls on the Secretary of State to alter the use classes to separate fast food take away shops from the other uses within the A3 category.

motionText_t: That this House believes that Planning Use Class A3, under the Town and Country Planning (Use Classes) Order 1987, is too wide, permitting change of use between restaurants, snack bars, hot food take away shops,  wine bars and public houses; notes that independent research carried out by the Department of the Environment found that hot food take aways had different planning implications, namely consistent late night noise and traffic parking problems; and calls on the Secretary of State to alter the use classes to separate fast food take away shops from the other uses within the A3 category.

docs.title_t: PATIENTS' RIGHTS IN SCOTTISH HEALTH BOARDS' PATIENTS' CHARTERS
title_s: PATIENTS' RIGHTS IN SCOTTISH HEALTH BOARDS' PATIENTS' CHARTERS
content_s: That this House urges each health board in Scotland to include in its patients' charter information
content_t: That this House urges each health board in Scotland to include in its patients' charter information concerning patient's rights in relation to transfer from an NHS bed to a private nursing home, and in particular to include a clear statement that if an elderly patient is transferred from an NHS bed to a private nursing home, the responsibility for payment lies with the hospital and not with the patient or their relatives or the Department of Social Security and also to include information on the patient's right to a second opinion, and their right to be treated in the hospital of their choice, and by the doctor of their choice.
motionText_s: That this House urges each health board in Scotland to include in its patients' charter information
motionText_t: That this House urges each health board in Scotland to include in its patients' charter information concerning patient's rights in relation to transfer from an NHS bed to a private nursing home, and in particular to include a clear statement that if an elderly patient is transferred from an NHS bed to a private nursing home, the responsibility for payment lies with the hospital and not with the patient or their relatives or the Department of Social Security and also to include information on the patient's right to a second opinion, and their right to be treated in the hospital of their choice, and by the doctor of their choice.

amendmentText_t: Line 1, leave out from 'House' to end and add 'notes the plethora of opinion polls, research and reports emanating from the Voluntary Euthanasia Society in recent years on end of life decision making; trusts that the raw data from which such opinion polls, research and reports have been compiled will be placed in the public domain; welcomes rigorous and independent research into end of life decision making whilst recognising that our priority should be the allocation od resources to support the dignity and independence of the seriously ill and severely disabled; and calls upon the Government to work closely with disability rights groups and the palliative care sector in order to safeguard the welfare of vunerable individuals at the end of their lives.'

content_t: That this House welcomes the Quality of Mercy report issued by the Voluntary Euthanasia Society; notes with concern the findings that 30 per cent. of those who assist in someone else's death in the United Kingdom go on to commit suicide; notes that there is a wide disparity between the penalties laid out in law and the number of prosecutions and sentences handed down; is concerned that unlike many other countries no formal research has been carried out into end-of-life decision-making in the United Kingdom; notes that members of the Council of Europe and the European Parliament have recently proposed that this issue should be researched and discussed in greater detail; and calls on the Government to carry out research into this issue as a matter of urgency.

docs.title_t: RICKSHAWS AND LONDON'S STATUS AS A WORLD CLASS CITY
title_s: RICKSHAWS AND LONDON'S STATUS AS A WORLD CLASS CITY
content_s: That this House notes with dismay the increasing number of pedicabs or rickshaws on the streets of L
content_t: That this House notes with dismay the increasing number of pedicabs or rickshaws on the streets of London; believes that passengers in pedicabs risk serious injury, since the construction and maintenance standards of pedicabs are unchecked and unregulated, and their riders often inexperienced about London's streets and traffic; further notes that pedicab fares are unregulated and are up to five times more than London taxi prices; records its concern, in light of the recent conviction of a pedicab rider for rape of a passenger, that pedicab riders are not subject to vetting, unlike taxi drivers; and believes that, far from being a colourful addition to the streetscape in our capital, pedicabs are a dangerous and expensive transport mode unneeded in a world class city.

content_t: That this House reaffirms its support for the policy of the Commonwealth and the United Nations which, in the light of the progress being made towards a united, non-racial and democratic South Africa, have agreed to the relaxation of the sports boycott of South Africa for those sports codes which have established a unified and genuinely non-racial governing body and which are pursuing a comprehensive programme for the development of the sport within black communities; welcomes the efforts of those sports codes which are seeking to meet these conditions; regrets the lack of progress in rugby union football, which has led the National and Olympic Sports Congress and the African National Congress to withdraw their support for any future international rugby tours; calls upon the South African Rugby Football Union to respond positively to the proposals put forward by the National and Olympic Sports Congress to overcome the current crisis; expresses its particular concern at the forthcoming tour of Wales by the Transvaal Rugby Football Union, which is to take place in defiance of direct appeals from the National and Olympic Sports Congress and the African National Congress; recognises that this tour falls outside the framework agreed by the Commonwealth for the relaxation of the sports boycott; and therefore calls upon the British Government to honour its responsibilities under the Gleneagles Agreement by urging the Welsh Rugby Union to postpone the tour and by providing no support or assistance to the tour should it take place.
after first 'rugby', insert 'union'.

motionText_t: That this House reaffirms its support for the policy of the Commonwealth and the United Nations which, in the light of the progress being made towards a united, non-racial and democratic South Africa, have agreed to the relaxation of the sports boycott of South Africa for those sports codes which have established a unified and genuinely non-racial governing body and which are pursuing a comprehensive programme for the development of the sport within black communities; welcomes the efforts of those sports codes which are seeking to meet these conditions; regrets the lack of progress in rugby union football, which has led the National and Olympic Sports Congress and the African National Congress to withdraw their support for any future international rugby tours; calls upon the South African Rugby Football Union to respond positively to the proposals put forward by the National and Olympic Sports Congress to overcome the current crisis; expresses its particular concern at the forthcoming tour of Wales by the Transvaal Rugby Football Union, which is to take place in defiance of direct appeals from the National and Olympic Sports Congress and the African National Congress; recognises that this tour falls outside the framework agreed by the Commonwealth for the relaxation of the sports boycott; and therefore calls upon the British Government to honour its responsibilities under the Gleneagles Agreement by urging the Welsh Rugby Union to postpone the tour and by providing no support or assistance to the tour should it take place.

docs.title_t: CONDUCT OF THE SECRETARY OF STATE FOR WALES (No. 4)
title_s: CONDUCT OF THE SECRETARY OF STATE FOR WALES (No. 4)
content_s: That this House calls upon the Secretary of State of Wales to withdraw his remarks about the Welsh r
content_t: That this House calls upon the Secretary of State of Wales to withdraw his remarks about the Welsh rugby team and teetotalism made in the Official Report, of 25th April, column 9, and, pending such withdrawal, calls upon the Welsh Rugby Union to suspend the provision of complimentary invitation tickets to the Committee Box for the Secretary of State for Wales in respect of (a) Welsh home internationals and (b) the SWALEC cup final; and calls upon the Secretary of State for Wales to follow the mature example of the Princess of Wales who never abuses the Welsh Rugby Union's hospitality and friendship in this way by making cheap remarks, based on total ignorance of Welsh rugby.

motionText_t: That this House calls upon the Secretary of State of Wales to withdraw his remarks about the Welsh rugby team and teetotalism made in the Official Report, of 25th April, column 9, and, pending such withdrawal, calls upon the Welsh Rugby Union to suspend the provision of complimentary invitation tickets to the Committee Box for the Secretary of State for Wales in respect of (a) Welsh home internationals and (b) the SWALEC cup final; and calls upon the Secretary of State for Wales to follow the mature example of the Princess of Wales who never abuses the Welsh Rugby Union's hospitality and friendship in this way by making cheap remarks, based on total ignorance of Welsh rugby.

title_s: RUGBY LEAGUE SILK CUT CHALLENGE CUP SEMI-FINALS
content_s: That this House notes with concern the fact that both Rugby League Silk Cut Challenge Cup semi-final
content_t: That this House notes with concern the fact that both Rugby League Silk Cut Challenge Cup semi-finals played on the 25th and 26th March are to be staged in Yorkshire, leaving the North West without a semi-final for the flagship event in the Rugby League calendar; believes that in the case of the Warrington Wolves versus Bradford Bulls match, to be held at Leeds Rugby League Football ground, this clearly puts Warrington supporters at a disadvantage being forced to travel beyond Bradford to Leeds; and calls on the Rugby Football League to ensure that venues are found which are convenient to both sets of supporters, and that the North West is not left without a Challenge Cup semi-final.

docs.title_t: MANCHESTER COMMONWEALTH GAMES AND RUGBY LEAGUE
title_s: MANCHESTER COMMONWEALTH GAMES AND RUGBY LEAGUE
content_s: That this House looks forward with great anticipation to the XVIIth Commonwealth Games in Manchester
content_t: That this House looks forward with great anticipation to the XVIIth Commonwealth Games in Manchester; believes it will be a tremendous celebration of the North West and its strong sporting heritage; expresses disappointment that while Rugby Union is included in the games, Rugby League, a sport holding a proud place in that heritage and played across the Commonwealth, will not feature; and while sending it every good wish for a successful games, asks the Commonwealth Games Federation to consider including Rugby League in the schedule of events for Melbourne 2006.

docs.title_t: AMICALE PARLEMENTAIRE DU RUGBY A TREIZE
title_s: AMICALE PARLEMENTAIRE DU RUGBY A TREIZE
content_s: That this House warmly welcomes the establishment of Amicale Parlementaire du Rugby a Treize, a Rugb
content_t: That this House warmly welcomes the establishment of Amicale Parlementaire du Rugby a Treize, a Rugby League Parliamentary Association in France; recalls that, in one of the most disgraceful episodes in sporting history, rugby league in that country was banned as a sport by the Vichy Government, its assets being removed and never returned; notes that the French Government's recent commission of inquiry into sport during the Occupation confirmed the injustice suffered by the treizistes; is concerned that the question of reparation has not so far been addressed; further notes that the European Commission has written to the French Government about discrimination against rugby league; welcomes the new Association's efforts to lift the ban on the sport being played in certain municipal stadia and campaign for its introduction into the curriculum for future PE teachers; wishes the Association well in its efforts on behalf of rugby league; and calls upon the British Government to support the European Commission's representations to the French Government.
motionText_s: That this House warmly welcomes the establishment of Amicale Parlementaire du Rugby a Treize, a Rugb
motionText_t: That this House warmly welcomes the establishment of Amicale Parlementaire du Rugby a Treize, a Rugby League Parliamentary Association in France; recalls that, in one of the most disgraceful episodes in sporting history, rugby league in that country was banned as a sport by the Vichy Government, its assets being removed and never returned; notes that the French Government's recent commission of inquiry into sport during the Occupation confirmed the injustice suffered by the treizistes; is concerned that the question of reparation has not so far been addressed; further notes that the European Commission has written to the French Government about discrimination against rugby league; welcomes the new Association's efforts to lift the ban on the sport being played in certain municipal stadia and campaign for its introduction into the curriculum for future PE teachers; wishes the Association well in its efforts on behalf of rugby league; and calls upon the British Government to support the European Commission's representations to the French Government.

content_s: That this House regrets Rugby Football Union proposals which will effectively downgrade the County C
content_t: That this House regrets Rugby Football Union proposals which will effectively downgrade the County Championship competition by the introduction of a new regional Super 8 tournament, as a result of which successful county sides such as Cornwall will no longer have access to players from National Leagues One, Two and Three, but only from South West One league and below; believes that one of the greatest strengths of English Rugby is the depth of grassroots support across local communities, nowhere more so than in Cornwall from where as many as 40,000 Cornish supporters have travelled to Twickenham to support their team in the county finals; concludes that a South Western team competing in a regional league is never going to achieve the same level of support whilst undermining the County Championship; and urges the RFU to reconsider.

content_t: That this House congratulates Cornwall on reaching the final of the County Rugby Championship which is to be held at Twickenham on Saturday 20th April; notes that Cornwall's allocation of 25,000 tickets have all been sold and that many of the tickets purchased from other sources have been by people and organisations with Cornish connections; acknowledges that there is tremendous pride in this Cornish rugby achievement and interest throughout the Duchy in the game on Saturday next; and calls upon the Chairman of the BBC to relax the conditions of the BBC's contract with the RFU as he did in the case of Cornwall's semi-final match so as to allow Television South West to televise the game live for the benefit of viewers living in Television South West's catchment area who are not able to attend the County final.

title_s: SOUTH AFRICAN RUGBY FOOTBALL UNION AND AMATEURISM
content_s: That this House, recalling that after considerable public pressure the South African Rugby Football
content_t: That this House, recalling that after considerable public pressure the South African Rugby Football Union recently lifted its ban on players also playing amateur rugby league, notes with interest the case of Mr Albertus Einslin who withdrew recently from amateur trials with Wakefield Trinity RLFC after being threatened with being banned for life from playing rugby union in South Africa; further notes that Mr Einslin has now accepted the offer of a ??30,000 a year job and expenses of ??200 to ??400 per match for playing rugby union with Western Provinces; wishes Mr Einslin well in his playing career; and calls upon the South African Rugby Football Union and the International Board of the Rugby Football Union to clarify exactly what is now meant by the amateurism principle in rugby union in South Africa and elsewhere.

motionText_t: That this House, recalling that after considerable public pressure the South African Rugby Football Union recently lifted its ban on players also playing amateur rugby league, notes with interest the case of Mr Albertus Einslin who withdrew recently from amateur trials with Wakefield Trinity RLFC after being threatened with being banned for life from playing rugby union in South Africa; further notes that Mr Einslin has now accepted the offer of a ??30,000 a year job and expenses of ??200 to ??400 per match for playing rugby union with Western Provinces; wishes Mr Einslin well in his playing career; and calls upon the South African Rugby Football Union and the International Board of the Rugby Football Union to clarify exactly what is now meant by the amateurism principle in rugby union in South Africa and elsewhere.

docs.title_t: SOUTH AFRICAN RUGBY UNION BAN ON AMATEUR RUGBY LEAGUE
title_s: SOUTH AFRICAN RUGBY UNION BAN ON AMATEUR RUGBY LEAGUE
content_s: That this House notes with extreme concern the decision of the South African Rugby Football Union to
content_t: That this House notes with extreme concern the decision of the South African Rugby Football Union to exclude persons who play amateur rugby league from also playing rugby union; believes that this policy is a clear breach of the previous international agreement between both sports; and calls upon the International Rugby Football Board to instruct the South African Rugby Football Union to immediately end this totally unacceptable discrimination, which is harmful to the development of international sporting relationships.

content_s: That this House, being aware of the important role that Moseley Rugby Club in Birmingham has played
content_t: That this House, being aware of the important role that Moseley Rugby Club in Birmingham has played over 130 years in developing rugby in the city and its wider catchment area of nearly five million people; views with concern the threatened relocation of the club to Oxford if it is sold to Oxford United Football Club, especially as this would deprive the Birmingham community of a major programme of rugby coaching which last year involved over 3,500 primary and secondary students from 60 schools; and therefore, calls on the Government to urge the RFU to continue to support the development of rugby in the Birmingham area, specifically by refusing to sanction any proposed move of Moseley Rugby Club to Oxford.

content_s: That this House views with concern the proposed merger between Bristol and Bath rugby clubs, and opp
content_t: That this House views with concern the proposed merger between Bristol and Bath rugby clubs, and opposes any proposal that will end the history of either club and their individual role within the life of their communities; notes that both clubs have long and distinguished histories and, given the importance of rugby union in the West of England, have made a valuable and ongoing contribution to the region's cultural heritage; recognises the contribution both clubs make to their communities, encouraging sporting participation at every level, and acting as a focus for local pride and identity; asks those who currently own the clubs to do all that they can to secure their independent identities for the future, and for the Rugby Football Union to refuse to sanction such a merger, or any move of these clubs from the communities that they represent; and calls on the Rugby Football Union to work towards a sustainable and stable future for rugby union that will make unnecessary further disruption to the sporting fabric of local communities.

content_s: That this House welcomes the decision of the Rugby Football Union to allow Essex County Rugby Footba
content_t: That this House welcomes the decision of the Rugby Football Union to allow Essex County Rugby Football Union to become a separate constitutent body, bringing to an end its 113 years' membership of the Eastern Counties Rugby Union; wishes the combined counties of Suffolk, Norfolk and Cambridgeshire, who will continue as the Eastern Counties, continued success; recognises that Essex County Rugby Football Union is worthy of being accepted by the Rugby Football Union as a constituent body in its own right; notes that previous applications in 1972, 1975 and 1977 were unsuccessful; congratulates all involved in the campaign on this occasion; believes that the formation of the new Essex County Rugby Football Union is in the best interests of the sport and all 43 clubs in the county; and looks forward to Essex becoming county champions.

motionText_t: That this House welcomes the decision of the Rugby Football Union to allow Essex County Rugby Football Union to become a separate constitutent body, bringing to an end its 113 years' membership of the Eastern Counties Rugby Union; wishes the combined counties of Suffolk, Norfolk and Cambridgeshire, who will continue as the Eastern Counties, continued success; recognises that Essex County Rugby Football Union is worthy of being accepted by the Rugby Football Union as a constituent body in its own right; notes that previous applications in 1972, 1975 and 1977 were unsuccessful; congratulates all involved in the campaign on this occasion; believes that the formation of the new Essex County Rugby Football Union is in the best interests of the sport and all 43 clubs in the county; and looks forward to Essex becoming county champions.

content_t: That this House congratulates the Halifax Schools Junior Rugby League team and their supporters on their magnificent victory at Wembley on 27th April; further congratulates the gallant losers, Runcorn, on their excellent performance; and notes that both teams brought great credit to the superb game of Rugby League.
